Both scaled and standardized data have the same purpose:

ğŸ‘‰ Make features comparable
ğŸ‘‰ Remove unit/scale differences
ğŸ‘‰ Help ML models work better

Example: Height (cm) and Salary (â‚¹) can be brought to similar scale.

âœ… Difference (Real-World Meaning)
1ï¸âƒ£ Min-Max Scaling (0â€“1 scaling)
scaled = (x - min) / (max - min)

Real-world meaning:

âœ” Converts values into a percentage-like form
âœ” 0 = minimum value in data
âœ” 1 = maximum value in data
âœ” Everything else falls between 0 and 1

Use when:
ğŸ‘‰ Data is bounded (marks, speed limits, age, etc.)
ğŸ‘‰ You want values in strict 0â€“1 range

Not good for:
âŒ Outliers (they stretch the scale)

2ï¸âƒ£ Standardization (Z-score normalization)
std = (x - mean) / std

Real-world meaning:

âœ” Converts values into how many standard deviations away from mean
âœ” Data becomes centered at 0
âœ” Spread becomes 1

Interpretation:

0 = average

+1 = one std above average

-1 = one std below average

Use when:
ğŸ‘‰ Data has normal/near-normal distribution
ğŸ‘‰ Models assume Gaussian data (ML, statistics)
ğŸ‘‰ Data has outliers â†’ less distortion than min-max

ğŸ¯ Super-short summary
Method	Real-world meaning	Best for
Scaled (0â€“1)	Percentage form	Bounded values, neural nets
Standardized (Z-score)	How far from average	Stats, ML models, outliers